history.content:
As mentioned in @4089, this is intentional / will not be resolved. The issue is not the classroom size.

Note that two sections are full, and only one has open seats, so it seems like this policy worked exactly as intended: it gave students flexibility, as opposed to forcing students to signing for section 2 (or not be able to sign up for the class).

children.subject: Well you don't know how many students will drop yet. This course doesn't start for another three months. When waitlisted you should always add a back-up course to your schedule, but it sounds like Babak advised you "hang in there" on the WL.

There's nothing different here than waitlisting from any other course. The class may try to expand, and it may or may not succeed; judging whether or not you'll get off the waitlist depends heavily on your position.

If waitlisted in this situation, should we enroll for a different class? I emailed Babak about this earlier and he responded with: "There's no discrepancy. Unfortunately,  the bottleneck is my TA budget, which I'm trying to resolve with the department. I won't get what I really want, but I'll do my best to absorb as much of the wait list as possible. Hang in there." So it seems to imply that there will be some sort of resolution?

history.content: 5/30 update: EE 120 was able to expand to 143. Everyone currently on the waitlist should be able to enroll if they choose an open REC section.

As mentioned, in one of the post below, there is a higher discussion rooms capacity for EE 120 then the lecture capacity, I was just wondering if/when will this be resolved? Is it just because a big enough room could not be found? If so would it be possible to just webcast the lecture. I know in @4089 it was mentioned that a few spots are left so students can change discussion sections but 23 seems like a lot.
